"Michael Moyer,""Reviewed in the United States on January 28, 2025"",""I wasn't sure what to expect with all the reviews kind of all over the place. But I find them to be a really good fit for my office, I set inside a small office and just outside the windows in the shop we have a lot of load testing going on. The headphones do a great job of silencing the noise out. I get great battery life out of them no issues and charge up time is quick. When I hook them up to my iPhone and the App it did an upgrade to the firmware I believe. So I have not experience and real bugs or issues. Overall really happy with them, I would recommend them. Oh one last thing the mic works great on the conference calls."""		
"David Diskin,""Reviewed in the United States on August 31, 2022"",""Because I do so many meetings over Teams (I'm a professional software trainer), I thought it would be time to finally invest in a really good headset. Up until now, I'd been using a $50 over-ear set by MPOW with a really nice boom mic. It was great, but it wasn't wireless, certainly wasn't portable, and didn't have the audio quality I'd want when listening to music."		
		
"I thought that by splurging more than $300 on a Sony product I'd get something that was beyond all of my expectations. I was almost right, but so very wrong in other ways."		
		
"CASE: Let's start here. The case is as slim as can be, very high-quality build, looks nice, feels nice, keeps everything protected. Excellent design here with one flaw: you can't really charge the headphones while they're snug in the case; they don't fold up the right way."		
		
"APP: To use most of the features, Sony requires you to download an app to your smartphone. That wasn't a big deal and the app was easy to figure out. It crashed twice on me (once during the first setup, again the next day). It offered some location-based services but I declined and it never asked me again. It wanted me to sign up for a free trial of some 360° music service -- not sure what that is, but I skipped it. I was disappointed that there wasn't a PC version of the app. For example, if I needed to switch which device the headphones were connected to, I can only do that from my phone -- that means my phone always has to be one of the two devices. There's no way to control the advanced features, or the equalizer, from the PC."		
		
"PAIRING: Bluetooth pairing was hit or miss, over and over again. If I were only pairing to my phone, I think it would be fine. But I wanted to also pair it to my desktop and laptop. The device supports pairing to two devices at the same time -- which was great -- but nearly every time I wanted to switch devices I had to literally turn off bluetooth so the headset would """"let go"""". Other times, upon reconnecting, the mic wouldn't work. Once, which turned out to be the final straw for me, was when I could not get the headset to work in Teams no matter what I tried, even though it worked fine a few hours earlier. (For context: I literally train employees and other trainers on how to use Teams, so I very much know what I'm doing.)"		
		
"SOUND QUALITY: Let me say that the sound quality IS exceptional. I had a blast listening to all my favorite songs streaming from my phone or laptop. I really can't understate the quality, base and treble. And the ANC (active noise cancelling) was AMAZING. I could be sitting right next to a whole house fan and not hear it. I was blown away."		
		
"RANGE: Twice during the day I tried walking around while on a call. It wasn't until I went downstairs that anyone said the quality of my voice had dropped. If I was less than 25 feet from the device, everything was great."		
		
BATTERY LIFE: After a day of use it was down to about 50% and that impressed me. Then I watched TV and ate dinner and later that evening I put on the headphones and realized that the battery dropped to 10%. I thought the system had an auto-off feature but something didn't quite work.		
		
"CHARGING: So after my surprise drop in battery, I plugged it into my desktop with a USB C cable I already had. A little light on the headset turned red. When I woke up the next morning, I was surprised to learn that the headphones were still at 10%. Apparently the USB C cable I use to charge my mouse won't charge the headphones. I guess you need to use the cable it ships with? I'm not sure what the deal was here, but that was pretty annoying."		
		
"CONTROLS: I found the touch/gesture controls to be mostly intuitive. Pro Tip: If you swipe up and hold your finger, the volume slowly increments up. Once, however, I accidentally hung up a Teams call when I was trying to adjust the volume. I love the feature that let's me hear ambient sound by cupping my hear -- super cool. Tap the power button to hear the battery level -- very nice touch! However, there's one extremely important flaw in the controls that I was shocked to discover. THERE IS NO MUTE BUTTON. The ONLY way to mute your mic during a call (Teams, phone, Zoom, etc) is to use the mute button on the desktop/phone. The headset, whose very first bullet is """"clear hands-free calling"""", has five built-in microphones, and a dedicated gesture to use Alexa... doesn't have a damn mute button. Sadly, the successor to this (the 1000XM5) has the same flaw."		
		
"Individually, the issues I raised wouldn't be enough for me to return the headset or give it a low rating. But for a $350 purchase, I expect it to be able to do what it says correctly. I expect a mute button. I expect it to power off when not in use. I expect any generic USB cable to work. I expect to be able to join a meeting without fussing with bluetooth."		
		
"I'd totally keep this if all I wanted it for was to listen to music."""		
"Kristen,""Reviewed in the United States on December 20, 2024"",""I'm coming to these from a pair of XB950BTs that I owned for like six years and repaired multiple times. The button controls were intuitive and out-of-the-way. I had reservations about touch pads on the ends of the headphones which have turned out to be valid. Even when I'm careful it's very easy to skip the song instead of adjusting the volume as intended. Sometimes double tapping to pause doesn't work. I often touch the headphone with my arm when exercising, activating it when I didn't want to. I don't even remember the touch features for the left side – too many options. In terms of the noise cancellation and ambient sound settings, it's annoying that I have to turn both off every single time instead of the headphones remembering my most recent selection. The sound is great and the nose cancelling, ambient sound & other features are cool. I just can't wait until this """"touchscreen"""" everything craze is over and we can go back to more practical, sensible, and simpler buttons like the XB950 had."""		
"Faith Adventure,""Reviewed in the United States on January 10, 2025"",These very comfortably padded Noise Cancelling Headphones are great. The sound quality is bountiful and full bodied. They are Bluetooth capable and although there's an app I simply plug and play. Voila all done! Very intuitive as it conveniently switches from listening to using the mic to answer phone calls and then resume your music where you left off. My sister-in-law is caring for her hubby who is in the mid stages of dementia. I suggested using these during times when he's resting so she can also relax with sounds to soothe her stress. I used them while caring for Mom as her dementia resulted in her speaking incessantly during the night. I stayed in the same room with her to keep her safe but I truly needed to cancel out the constant sounds and these were stress reducing & sanity saving. Really happy that I was able to get them during a flash sale for a reduced price."		
"Jim,""Reviewed in the United States on October 22, 2024"",""These were by far the very best noise cancelling headphones out there imho. Superior in all categories. Noise cancelling, comfort, sound quality, ease of use, customization via the mobile app. All fantastic."		
		
"I wear mine all night long. Both to fall asleep listening to whatever, and to noise cancel my wife's snoring. So it was not surprising to me after years of ownership that the right swivel broke. Not a problem. There's a guy on YouTube that sells both left and right swivel repair kits, and has a very detailed video showing exactly how to fix it. Highly recommended if that happens to yours."		
		
"While searching for a swivel fix, I happened across some videos about squealing. Mine were not doing that. I thought, """"You poor bastids. That's a bummer."""" Wouldn't you know it, about 1 month later, mine started squealing. It's the worst when first powered on. No matter what is set in the app, when powered on, noise cancelling is full on. It starts as a tinny sound in the right ear, and invariably gets worse, until it makes an intolerably loud squealing sound that will not go away at first. Move the right cup off of my ear, and it stops. Back on the ear, and full sqeal again. Turning off noise cancelling makes it stop. That's a bit inconvenient, because I connect to other devices. You have to connect to the phone, to run the app, to turn off noise cancelling."		
		
"For mine, within about 30 minutes I can turn noise cancelling back on, and no squeal. They then act and sound like brand new, and stay that way no matter what Bluetooth device I connect to until powered down and up again."		
		
"From what I've read, for those experiencing it, the phenomenon acts differently for different users."		
		
There is a microphone in the right ear cup that provides the noise cancelling capability. I've seen YouTube videos of people attempting to replace the microphone. But none with success that I've found.		
		
"So, that is my take on the down side to them from my years of ownership. I still love them though, even with that annoyance. I would be willing to accept more weight, if it made the battery last longer between charges. But other than that, the noise cancelling (when working correctly), the sound quality, and wearing comfort are fantastic."""		
